# Road to Next.js - Project Overview

This is a **Next.js 16** application following the [Road to Next.js course](https://www.road-to-next.com) with some personal adjustments. The project is a ticket management system called "TicketBounty" that allows users to create tickets with bounties, manage organizations, and collaborate on tickets.

## Project Context

- **Framework**: Next.js 16.1.1 with App Router
- **Language**: TypeScript (strict mode)
- **Course**: Based on Road to Next.js course (https://www.road-to-next.com)
- **Note**: This implementation includes personal adjustments and modifications from the original course

## Key Technologies

- **React**: 19.2.3 with React Compiler enabled
- **Database**: PostgreSQL with Prisma ORM
- **Authentication**: Better Auth
- **State Management**: TanStack Query (React Query)
- **Forms**: React Hook Form with Zod validation
- **Styling**: Tailwind CSS 4 with shadcn/ui components
- **Email**: React Email with Resend
- **Background Jobs**: Inngest
- **Linting/Formatting**: Biome
- **URL State**: nuqs for search params management

## Project Structure

The project follows a feature-based architecture:

```
src/
├── app/              # Next.js App Router pages and layouts
├── components/       # Shared UI components
├── features/         # Feature modules (auth, ticket, comment, etc.)
├── lib/              # Core utilities and configurations
├── emails/           # Email templates
└── utils/            # Utility functions
```

## General Guidelines

1. **Always use TypeScript** - Strict mode is enabled
2. **Follow feature-based organization** - Group related code by feature
3. **Use server actions** for mutations (see `server-actions.mdc`)
4. **Data fetching is server-first** - Almost all queries happen in Server Components calling query functions.
5. **Client side fetching** - Rare, only when when a specific feature needs it (Right now I use @tanstack/query `useInfiniteQuery()` for infinite scroll feature and nothing else)
6. **Validate with Zod** - All form inputs and API data should be validated
7. **Use Biome** for formatting and linting (run `pnpm check` before committing)
8. **Path aliases** - Use `@/` prefix for imports from `src/`
9. **Server components by default** - Use client components only when needed

## Code Style

- **Quotes**: Single quotes (configured in Biome)
- **Line width**: 100 characters
- **Indentation**: Tabs
- **Compact formatting**: Prefer fewer lines when code fits within the line length limit and Biome formatting rules. For example, prefer `await prisma.model.update({ where: { id }, data });` over multi-line formatting when it fits on one line.
- **Naming**:
  - Components: PascalCase
  - Files: camelCase for utilities, PascalCase for components
  - Folders: kebab-case

## Development Commands

- `pnpm dev` - Start development server
- `pnpm build` - Build for production
- `pnpm check` - Run Biome check and format
- `pnpm tsc` - Type check without emitting
- `pnpm email` - Preview email templates

## Important Patterns

- **Server Actions**: Use `'use server'` directive. Preferred pattern: direct async calls returning `ActionResult<T>` with `actionSuccess()`/`actionError()` helpers. Legacy pattern: FormData + ActionState for form POSTs (see `server-actions.mdc`)
- **Queries**: Almost always done server-side in Server Components. Client-side only for infinite scroll with `useInfiniteQuery()`
- **Database**: Use Prisma client from `@/lib/prisma`
- **Authentication**: Use `getSessionUserOrRedirect()` or `getSessionUserOrUndefined()` from `@/lib/auth/session`

